The franchise sale of his hotel helped Lukas Pytloun well for the place of winner of the competition of the best Individual Entrepreneur.
The winner of last year’s competition for the best individual entrepreneur was Lukas Pytloun, a 28-year-old entrepreneur.
His adventure towards success is like in a movie.
Lukas Pytloun loved to travel.
And abroad, he realized that in Libérec there was a lack of a quality hosting site at a reasonable price.
From his savings on what he had earned when he worked abroad and with the help of a bank loan he bought a small building of 5 apartments half demolished.
Knowing that he was still a third-year graduate student, it was a courageous action.
“The relationship between the quality and the price of accommodation in our region made me want to do something,” says Lucas Pytloun.
He began renting the first rebuilt apartment to foreign workers.
He reinvested the profit in the building which he transformed into a pension with 54 beds.
Since then, his entrepreneurial activity has allowed him to open in Libérec 4 guesthouses, two stylish restaurants and two hotels with a total capacity of nearly 300 beds of all categories of accommodation.
The most comfortable of them was until very recently the four-star Pytloun design hotel.
This year, another one of the same quality happened to him.
"We just signed a contract with a hotel in Ostrov U Tise where we sold our franchise concept and other candidates for the Pytloun hotel franchise showed up," the number 1 entrepreneur of last year.
"And for the sale of the license for the operation of a large-scale hotel the victory in the Entrepreneur of the Year competition served well," adds Pytloun with gratitude.
The victory brought him more popularity and to be known in and around Liberec.
“People recognized me on the streets, congratulated me often and, I have to say, it was very pleasant,” he recalls.
He recommends participation in this competition to anyone who is trying to do something.
It is not necessary to win but every opportunity to be visible is good.
He says he uses his contacts and acquaintances to this day that he could not have obtained otherwise.
"With those I met through the competition I started to have regular business relationships.
According to him, the fame related to the success has also had an impact on the employees.
And he's about 70.
“I observe in them above all the loyalty and pride of having engaged in something that has been generally recognized.”
"This is not, and by far, the only result of my personal work, but the result of good work from all of us together.
“Only my name is pushed forward,” says Lucas Pytloun modestly.
I wish my successor a better year than we had at Farmet.
The euphoria of victory was quickly replaced by the effects of the crisis.
Thanks to the sense of purpose the winner Farmet has the worst moments behind it.
The one who came to pick up the prize in Slovansky dum for the first place of the contest for the Firm of the Year organized by Vodaphone last year is Karel Zdarsky the owner of the company Farmet.
The jury has rewarded the efforts with which it has transformed a tooling workshop in Ceska Skalice into a firm with a turnover of 100 million crowns.
"I can say that the award has encouraged not only me but also my collaborators and has increased our self-confidence to fight the competition," said the winner of last year's competition.
At the beginning of the history of the Farmet company there was the desire to do something useful.
And so when the state proposed to Karel Zdrasky's father to rent the small workshop as compensation after the confiscation of property by the communists, he did not hesitate for a long time, refused a career in a firm where he worked at the time, and created a company with some comrades in his father's entourage for the manufacture of plastic bathtubs.
Not long after they began to specialize in vegetable oil presses.
After eighteen years, it became the largest manufacturer of automatic presses in Central Europe.
The company has been known even among the non-specialized public after the success achieved in the competition through the media.
“Not only have our customers begun to really get to know the Farmet brand better, but also foreign partners who have begun to realize that they are collaborating with a company that has achieved the greatest success in their home country,” says Karel Zdarsky.
But last year did not happen at Farmet only in the euphoria of victory.
The company's valuation was based on the economic results of 2008 and partly of 2009.
And precisely in 2009 it was the most difficult year for the sale of engineering machines.
At the height of the crisis, which did not really affect citizens, societies were forced to stop their investment projects and start limiting their purchases of new materials and technologies.
“We obviously did not escape this situation.”
"The turnover fell by 40 percent, and we had to limit our production and even lay off," says Karel Zdarsky.
A viable society needs to know that unpopular measures need to be taken from time to time.
