The regulated rents people pay in nearly 300,000 apartments could increase next year by 10 percent.
Czech children get drunk on rum and fernet. Beer is no longer fashionable and acts very slowly.
The fernet, rum, vodka and exceptionally also the best brand of whisky are stolen from the parents.
These are drinks that most often bring those who get drunk, who are not yet fifteen years old, into the hands of the doctor.
Children who are treated in hospital for recidivism are no exception.
This results from the experience of doctors who encounter cases similar to the admissions of children's departments of hospitals.
“Beer or wine is no longer fashionable because it takes time to get drunk.”
"The trend is really to strong alcohols," said Pravo Ludek Pelikan, head of the children's department at the Horovice hospital in central Bohemia.
“When they manage to chip a dad bottle in the closet, it’s sometimes whisky but it’s the fernet and the vodka that prevail.”
“Vodka has this advantage that they can mix it with fruit juice and thus not smell it,” explains the head of the department.
Eva Jurinova, spokeswoman for the Motol hospital, is also right.
"In general, it's rum or fernet."
"It's now alcohol in fashion especially in elementary schools."
"In some cases, it was slivovice that they brought from the house," Jurinova added.
According to the head of the Pélikan department, seeing drunk children aged thirteen to fourteen on hospital admissions is a normal phenomenon.
Before working in Horovice since last year, he was in Motol where he practiced ten years precisely in pediatrics where ambulances brought schoolchildren from the wide surroundings completely drunk.
"A young girl was hospitalized like this four times
“She began her career at the age of 12 when she was brought in with 3.5 per thousand alcohol in her blood and a mixture of ecstasy,” the doctor said.
"She was at the Holesovice Exhibition Park at a party."
“What’s interesting is that it didn’t seem odd to the mother that her daughter was away for 48 hours,” the department director said.
It is precisely the disinterest of the parents or their extraordinary tolerance of the fact that their offspring indulge in drinking that are the main cause of the development of alcoholism in children.
According to specialists, however, we are not talking about addiction, in its strict sense, for children.
"Under the word alcoholic we mean a chronic dependence on alcohol of several years with all the phenomena that result from it but that we do not find in children."
"In those who use alcohol on a regular basis, it is rather a significantly unfavorable socio-family background," explained Department Head Pélikan.
According to spokeswoman Jurinova, about forty drunk children were hospitalized this year until mid-November in the pediatric clinic in Motol.
Only cases with severe intoxication requiring hospitalization are included in the statistic.
Drunk children who are after emergency care taken home by parents or by the police are not counted.
In addition to the cases of children who sit down and drink a bottle of alcohol after school, it exists according to Pélikan three seasonal waves with which we can count: the day of the witches, New Year's Eve and the end of the school year.
"Either they drink out of spite after bad results or on the contrary they celebrate the start of the holidays."
"Of course, I experienced the admission of seven drunken children at one time on Witches' Day," Pelikan said.
The drunken child who spent the night in the hospital in detoxification under medical control is paradoxically in a better position than the one who returned home and suffers the next day from the "hangover".
Morning headaches caused by dehydration and a lack of glucose are eliminated by an infusion of glucose and nutrients that the body needs.
"They are better off because they have an excellent evening and then a gentle awakening and nothing hurts them."
“They’re just amazed at where they are,” Pelikan adds, knowing that from time to time it spoils patients’ good mood at least with the bill for their care.
Transportation by ambulance and hospitalization on an intensive care bed can be up to tens of thousands of crowns.
“From time to time, I have applied this as a means of education by counting on these children how much their drunkenness cost and that they could spend the whole summer on seasonal work to pay for a single evening,” Pelikan added.
However, according to him, health insurance companies in their regressive managements, which are expected to recover care-related expenses from parents, do not deal with cases of drunken children.
Two L-159 aircraft are for the first time in foreign hands in Spain.
Two of the five L-159s, for which the Ministry of Defence exchanged Casa C-295M transport aircraft, took off on Tuesday for Seville, Spain, where the aircraft manufacturer Casa-EADS is based.
This is the first time that aircraft of this type have become the property of someone other than the Czech army.
However, they have been abroad in the course of exercises or demonstration flights.
These are the two-seater versions of the L-159T1 that were until now in service in the Czech Army and that were in flight condition.
The three remaining aircraft are single-seat versions of the L-159.
These are currently stationed at Aero Vodochody and the commercial intermediary - the firm Omnipol - took them into account last week.
According to Jan Pejsek of the press department of the Ministry of Defense, the physical departure of Vodochody's planes is currently unknown.
“The L-159 single-seater aircraft planned for the exchange were taken on long-stored aircraft without causing additional charges or investments for the Ministry of Defense.”
"The two-seater L-159 T1s have been exchanged in the state," said Pravo Pejsek.
He added that the army will not remain without two-seaters since the ministry signed in May 2009 with Aero Vodochody an agreement worth 200 million crowns for the transformation of four unused L-159 single-seaters into two two-seaters.
The army took delivery of the first aircraft in July, with the second scheduled for delivery at the end of this year.
According to Pejsek EADS has committed to introduce the aircraft in the equipment of some Alliance countries.
"The contract clearly states that the L-159 aircraft are EADS and will be used to train pilots from NATO member countries."
"It is therefore up to the person who considers how to do this," Pejsek said.
Hospodarske noviny announced some time ago that the Spanish army is not interested in the L-159.
The exchange of five L-159s for a Casa aircraft and the purchase of three other aircraft for 3.5 billion crowns was approved last year by the government of Mirek Topomanek.
The Ministry of Defence did not call for tenders and contacted EADS directly.
the defence management argued that the exchange ensures a future export of the L-159 abroad.
The Czech army bought 72 aircraft from Aero Vodochody and uses only 24, wanting to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa aircraft is likely to have legal implications.
However, the European Commission has filed a complaint against the Czech Ministry of Defence with the European Court of Justice because the aircraft should have been chosen as part of a European-wide call for tenders and in no case by contacting a manufacturer directly.
The army has already taken delivery of three Casa aircraft, the last is expected to arrive at Prague Kbely airport in two weeks.
An index longer than the annular is a sign of low risk of cancer
Men who have the index finger longer than the ring finger are at a lower risk of having prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This can depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our findings show that relative finger length serves as a simple test for prostate cancer risk, especially for men before the age of 60," said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, including by combining it with genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health history, Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009 she followed with her colleagues in Britain more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had the index finger of their right hand shorter than the ring finger.
For them as for the 19 percent of those who had fingers of the same length, we found the same probability of prostate cancer.
In the case of those who had the index finger longer than the ring finger, however, the risk fell to 33 percent, for men before age 60, the risk decreased to 87 percent.
The length ratio of the two fingers cited - formed during the prenatal period - indicates in particular different levels of sex hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research has shown that it is testosterone that helps the development of prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, told CTK he was aware of the study but did not believe the relationship between finger length and cancer was "completely demonstrated".
