Mysterious earthworks
The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) has new information on a nuclear program developed by Syria.
But this country refuses to take a position on this issue, let alone submit to the agency's controls.
On the night of 5-6 September 2007 at about midnight, at least four Israeli F-15 I fighter jets attacked a mysterious cubic-shaped building on Syrian territory.
It is located on the bank of the Euphrates; the largest nearby city is 30 kilometers away: it is Dair as-Sur.
Its name appears in IAEA documents, because it refers to the reactor that Syria has built with the help of North Korea in stone parallelepiped, hidden in a valley marked by the absence of electricity.
According to a briefing by the US intelligence services, the CIA, dating from the end of April 2008, the current reactor, known as the neighboring locality, el-Kibar, would be well able to produce plutonium, which would allow the manufacture of atomic weapons.
On the other hand, this technique has been valid since the 1950s.
The CIA showed a presentation video with blurred satellite images.
Through computer-aided animation, it indicated the likely location of each reactor component prior to the destruction of the power plant, which represents a miniature copy of the North Korean model of the Yongbyon nuclear power plant.
In addition, she presented the photos showing the building located nearby, or even inside it.
It seems that the reactor was about to be put into service, but it was not yet equipped with fuel rods.
Today, more than three years after the Israeli bombing, there is barely more information available than at the time, and even, with time, the mystery thickens more and more.
Former U.S. President George W. Bush recently revealed in his memoirs that before this attack, the CIA was sure that Syria had built a reactor at el-Kibar, but had little evidence that the country was developing “an active nuclear weapons program.”
Some intelligence agents in Europe prefer to be more cautious about it and only speak of a “presumed reactor”, even though they consider the CIA’s presentation “plausible”.
They lack tangible evidence, as does the IAEA.
Asked how he made sure he was dealing with a nuclear reactor, a senior U.N. diplomat gave only a laconic response in the summer, saying the IAEA had “enough documents to ask questions.”
The Syrians certainly hastily removed the rubble of the "unused military building" and proceeded to a methodical flattening of the ground.
However, in June 2008, a team of IAEA experts led by former Chief Inspector Oli Heinonen discovered traces of human-produced uranium in al-Kibar.
In addition, the IAEA received through a Member State satellite images of commercial providers showing the moment that directly followed the attack. it seems that the latter are more eloquent than those presented by the CIA.
However, these photos are not available on the market because the anonymous sponsor, perhaps Israel, acquired them exclusively.
It is therefore impossible for the IAEA to establish their authenticity objectively.
Syria has always assured that it has never carried out a secret atomic program and that it has not built a reactor.
Damascus claims that the uranium found at the site comes from weapons used by Israel.
But the IAEA rejected this argument after analyzing the particles, calling it implausible.
Since that time, Damascus has refused any discussion about this, as well as about satellite images.
In addition, Syria does not allow the controllers to carry out a second inspection at the site of el-Kibar and denies access to the rubble of the building destroyed by the bomb.
But even Israel keeps a stubborn silence.
Confirming the official position, Ehud Olmert, then Prime Minister-in-Office at the time of the attack, recently said: “We will never comment on this.”
Thus, the investigation into this case has been ongoing since June 2008 without reaching a result and it is "increasingly turning into a serious problem of the Agency's credibility", as acknowledged by a high-ranking Western diplomat serving at IAEA headquarters in Vienna, in the end it is a serious violation of the Treaty on the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons.
The IAEA believes that in order to make progress, it is necessary to clarify the existence of the other three facilities that must have a "functional relationship" with the alleged reactor.
To date, the inspectors have not indicated what facilities are here, what their function is or what they are suspected of containing.
According to information published by the newspaper "Süddeutsche Zeitung", they are known within the IAEA respectively under the names of Marj as-Sultan, Masyaf and Iskandariyah also from the names of neighboring cities.
The Independent Institute for Science and International Security in Washington identified these locations and discovered on satellite images a complex near Masyaf that would most likely be one of the suspicious objects.
It may be at or directly adjacent to a military base, which is exactly why Syria is denying IAEA inspectors access to the three sites.
In Vienna, it is alleged that the Syrians fear that the inspection group is actually spies who would be sent on behalf of the United States by the IAEA to spy on military installations.
Actually, it was intelligence provided by U.S. intelligence agents that caught the attention of nuclear inspectors.
The IAEA has information, including satellite photos, indicating that vehicles made shuttles between the three sites and the stone parallelepiped to transport substances.
A senior Western diplomat said in Vienna that at least one of the facilities could “serve for fuel production.”
It would have "no indications concerning sensitive activities", such as enrichment and reprocessing of uranium; processes that are indispensable to the production of atomic weapons.
This type of reactor certainly works thanks to unenriched uranium.
Nevertheless, there are plausible assumptions about the fundamental questions of where the uranium should have come from and where the plutonium needed to make the bomb would have been later separated.
It is not known whether the rubble, which could hide high-value traces, was stored at all three sites.
When the hundreds of truckloads of dirt are gone, no one will have information on where the debris is stored.
For the IAEA, it is unlikely that Syria had the al-Tibni salt mine, located just a few kilometres from el-Kibar on the other side of the Euphrates, examined in 1998 to see if it could be suitable for storing radioactive waste.
Recently analyzing satellite photos taken for the famous Jane's Intelligence Review magazine, former IAEA inspector Robert Kelley linked them to the reactor in question.
Satellite photos, however, show Syria undertook earthworks at the three suspect sites and moved huge containers when the IAEA began demanding access to those sites.
It may be a coincidence, but it did not help to rule out suspicions.
It was said in diplomatic circles that the IAEA had spent several months developing a plan for the inspections to be carried out there, which was intended to allow Syria to preserve possible military secrets. Only the time invested shows how much interest the inspectors have in this case.
Meanwhile, Damascus also ignored this proposal.
A year ago, if the Western diplomats in Vienna had not reported the destruction of the reactor, the urgency would not be signalled for this case, says, for example, Glyn Davies, the ambassador of the United States who has been talking for a few months about what is known as the special inspections, one of the most powerful means that the Atomic Agency has at its disposal to put into action.
IAEA Director Yukiya Amano, who had to propose these inspections, has already spoken of "an option to which I am open in the future", but he is still hesitant.
This means a huge risk: on the one hand, it requires a majority on the IAEA Board of Governors and many of the 35 countries represented there have no desire to see the situation escalate.
On the other hand, as that diplomat who gives to reflect: "What good would it do, if in the end they find nothing"
