The tip of the feet towards the center
In the weeks after she suddenly became a widow, Argentina’s president, Cristina Fernández, has enjoyed a wave of public sympathy that has improved her approval rating from 20 points to more than 50 percent, its highest level since she was elected in 2007.
Yet turning that into a successful campaign for a second term in an election next year could depend on Mrs. Fernández’s choice, visibly in mourning, whether or not she would abandon the intransigence of her late husband, predecessor and former political partner, Néstor Kirchner.
In this regard, the signs remain confusing.
Mr. Kirchner, who continued to manage economic policy even after his wife succeeded him as president, used to develop budgets that underestimated tax revenues, economic growth and inflation.
This allowed the first couple to spend the extra income at will.
Mrs. Fernández’s government lost its majority in Congress last year, on paper.
But the opposition is divided, and the situation has plunged into disarray following Mr. Kirchner's death from a heart attack on October 27.
Some of the dissident members of the ruling Peronist movement have joined Ms. Fernández.
But after chaotic sessions (where a parliamentarian slapped one of his peers in the face and others accused the government of corruption), Congress does not have to approve the 2011 budget.
“I’m not going to argue,” the president said.
Currently, the 2010 budget will be implemented next year, giving the president even more room to spend at will.
The economy is vastly overheating: it is likely to grow by nearly 9% this year.
The official rate of inflation now stands at 11.1% but many private estimates and union wage demands see this figure close to 30%.
Kirchner, who took office in 2003 when Argentina feared economic collapse, made growth and poverty reduction a priority, rather than controlling inflation.
He refused to deal with the IMF, harassed the private sector, and purged INDEC, the statistical office, which falsified official inflation statistics.
Can Mrs Fernández now moderate these policies?
She called for talks between private companies and union leaders.
And his officials say they want to limit next year's pay rises to 18%.
The economy has been boosted by high world prices for Argentina's agricultural exports.
But inflation eroded the growth boost following a sharp devaluation in 2002.
Perhaps that is why Mrs Fernández is showing signs of wanting to restore Argentina's financial relations with the rest of the world.
This year, the government reached an agreement with bondholders who had refused a previous forced debt restructuring for which Argentina had not settled its maturities in 2001.
Now Ms Fernandez seems to be edding towards an agreement with creditor governments grouped in the Paris Club, to which it owes some $6.7 billion.
The Kirchners have always insisted that this could not involve surveillance by the IMF, as is customary.
But last month, Amado Boudou, the Minister of Economy, announced that the Fund would provide "technical assistance" to design a new national index of consumer prices; which looks like a prelude to the sanitation of the INDEC.
It is unclear whether Ms. Fernández wants to remain in politics beyond the end of her term, now that her husband is no longer with her.
If it does, it needs to gain the support of the middle class, among which Kirchnerism is highly advocated.
When the Argentines return from their summer vacation in March, the wave of sympathy for her will have ebbed.
If she wants to win another election, she will have to decide whether or not to repudiate, quietly, her husband’s many policies.
