Prosecutors will not indict Senator Ensign
Justice Department prosecutors have lifted criminal charges against Senator John Ensign, stemming from a case involving a former campaign assistant and his efforts to get a lobbying job for the woman's husband, the senator's lawyers announced Wednesday.
The ruling ends the most serious legal threat facing Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was considered a potential Republican candidate for the 2012 presidential election until the scandal surrounding his case made national headlines last year and hurt his career.
Mr Ensign’s office said he was “very happy” with the decision, the result of a year-long investigation.
The senator could still be exposed to disciplinary action by the Senate Ethics Committee.
Mr. Ensign's lawyers said the Department of Justice had "informed Senator Ensign that he is no longer being investigated and that he does not intend to maintain any charges against him in this case."
The Department of Justice has refrained from commenting on this.
The announcement came as a sort of surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Department of Justice, who said there was significant evidence indicating that Mr. Ensign conspired to violate a federal criminal prohibition on lobbying.
Interviews, emails and other documents, first released in October 2009 in the New York Times, indicated that Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, get a lucrative lobbying job to win the silence of Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, over the senator’s affair with her.
Ms. Hampton once served as a treasurer during an Ensign campaign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political donors to find work for Mr. Hampton and then defended their rights after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them; in accordance with the documents and interviews.
As Mr. Hampton had recently been an employee of Mr. Ensign, he was prohibited by law for one year from lobbying his former employer or the Senate as a whole.
Ethics experts have argued that the unusual agreement between Ensign and Hampton, who were close friends before the case, appears to contradict the so-called lobbying revolving door ban.
“There appears to be prima facie evidence of a conspiracy to violate and substantial violation of the revolving door law,” said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients of a government investigation.
Although the department's judge declined to explain the reasoning that led to the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said the department appeared to be wary of political prosecution after a number of high-level setbacks by its public integrity section, including last year's decision to drop prosecution of the former senator.
Federal prosecutors are clearly afraid to take up arms, said Melanie Sloan, the Chief Citizens for Accountability and Ethics in Washington, a advocacy group that has received several complaints against Ensign in the case.
"This basically says high-ranking government officials can now assume the laws don't apply to them," she added.
Paul Coggins, Ensign’s lead lawyer, said in an interview that he received a phone call Monday from a Justice Department prosecutor and follow-up the next day, telling him the department was not seeking charges against his client.
Ensign’s team of lawyers had cooperated with prosecutors to try to persuade them that the senator, as his office reaffirmed Wednesday in a statement, “had acted in accordance with the law.”
Mr. Coggins declined to clarify the legal arguments he had made to the prosecutor's office.
“I’m not comfortable going into the details of my discussions with the Justice Department, except to say that we think they made the right decision,” he said.
Last month, the Federal Elections Commission decided to drop an investigation following an independent complaint by the ethics group, arguing that Ensign’s parents’ payment of $96,000 to the Hamptons violated federal election law.
The election commission said it did not have enough evidence to prove that the money was anything but a gift.
NV Energy, a large Nevada company that has long supported the senator, is a company for which Mr. Ensign helped Mr. Hampton find lobbying work.
An email sent in December 2008 showed that after the company welcomed Mr. Hampton as a lobbyist, Mr. Ensign's chief of staff, John Lopez, contacted Mr. Hampton and told him that he was "hammering" the Home Office on a matter in dispute.
Mr. Ensign also attended a luncheon with Mr. Hampton and another Nevada client, Allegiant Air, and asked the Secretary of Transportation to arrange a meeting on behalf of the airline after he hired Mr. Hampton to lobby.
When news of the case surfaced last year, Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned from his position as fourth-ranking Republican leader in the Senate.
After maintaining a low profile for several months, Mr. Ensign said two weeks ago that he intended to run for a third term in the Senate.
Announcing that Ensign was no longer the target of a criminal investigation, his spokeswoman, Jennifer Cooper, said the senator hoped the ethics committee would quickly follow the Department of Justice's lead and end its investigation.
Senator Ensign is pleased to continue her hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada, she said.
