In the end, the defense said there were more than 140,000 messages about the rape case trial and the children attached to their beds in a house that was set on fire.
On Thursday, the widely followed trial of Steven J. Hayes, who was convicted of the murder of three members of the Cheshire family in Connecticut, is expected to lead to an official end where the judge would impose the death penalty, voted by the jury.
But Mr. Hayes' lawyers have already filed evidence in court that outlines arguments for appeal, likely to occupy the courts for years to come.
What is provocative is that the intense reporting on the trial – as well as the widespread and widespread use by Twitter journalists – have created a “circus atmosphere”, a saturation so widespread and instantaneous with incendiary details that the jury was badly influenced by the passions of the public.
The request could prompt appeal judges to debate whether new technologies require new rules in courtrooms.
"I experienced it in this trial; I think there is a real danger, the introduction of new technologies in courtrooms is infringing on human rights to a fair trial," said Thomas J. Ullmann, a lawyer for Hayes, Chief Counsel.
Trial judge Jon C. Bleue of the State Superior Court laconically rejected the claims in last week’s ruling, saying the media were “prudently controlled” and there was no evidence that the jury was driven by passion.
