Courts of appeal have recognized for decades that media coverage of notorious cases can raise questions about the fairness of a trial.
In a landmark 1966 judgment, the U.S. Supreme Court overturned the conviction of a Cleveland osteopath, Dr. Sam Sheppard, for the murder of his wife, arguing in his ruling that there was a “carnival atmosphere at trial” because of the media.
The crime is considered by some to have been the inspiration for the television show and film "The Fugitive".
Some lawyers have argued that appeal courts seized to review Mr. Hayes' conviction half a century later may be curious given the argument that new rules may be needed to manage courtroom media, unimaginable at the time of Dr. Sheppard's case.
“There is a general reason to worry about the impact of new media” in large-scale trials, said John J. Donohue III, a professor at Stanford Law School who studied the death penalty in Connecticut and wrote a report that it has been arbitrarily enforced.
Professor Donohue says some appeal judges may be intrigued by the idea that limiting instant communication from courtrooms could allow for fairer trials.
Twitter's case is just one of many described by Hayes's lawyers, likely to be discussed for years, delaying execution.
Defense lawyers also argue, for example, that Mr. Hayes was allegedly harmed when Judge Blue refused to allow them to test the reactions of potential jurors by showing them macabre photos of criminal scenes during jury selection.
