Defense lawyers say they will also challenge the constitutionality of the death penalty and will argue that the judge unfairly expelled one of the jurors, who had been critical of prosecutors, and that he improperly pressured for a verdict by making the unusual decision to get the jury to deliberate on a weekend.
The jurors were not kidnapped.
But their arguments about the effect of the intense media coverage of the trial could be the biggest source of interest.
They noted in a challenge to the verdict, filed last month, that the case dominated the media scene in Connecticut and was discussed during the election campaign by candidates for governor and the U.S. Senate.
They maintained that the computer media kept stoking the flames of the emotion of the case.
“The daily squabble of media tweets, cameras and journalists outside the courthouse,” the lawyers wrote, “was nothing like what had been seen before here in New Haven, and perhaps even nationally.”
Their focus on Twitter system coverage is controversial.
In interviews, some journalists said the claim that snapshots were more incendiary than slower releases was a luddite view that would impoverish the Court’s policy governing media coverage of future trials.
But some lawyers said appeals courts were often drawn to arguments that social and technological change required court adaptation.
Mr. Hayes’s lawyers insist on this claim.
In their file, they make a reference to the 1966 Supreme Court ruling that reversed Dr. Sheppard's conviction because of the media coverage of the trial and they made it clear that they would invoke the need for new rules for new media.
“This case,” they wrote, “represents that of Sheppard v. Maxwell of the 21st century.”
Can civility bring cleavages closer together?
After a campaign marked by invective and negativity, a minimum of civility erupted in Washington this week.
Is this a warning sign of genuine bipartisan cooperation forward or an illusory moment before the rapid return to the partisan struggle in the capital?
Tuesday’s meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders produced no breakthrough on the major issues that need to be addressed during the “lame duck” session.
But obviously, there was at least a polite discussion about the differences between the two parties as well as the recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each side wanted to score points.
Wednesday’s public meeting of the committee on the president’s deficit was equally civilized, despite political differences that remain among members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created a mutual respect transcending the ideological gap; but which, however, still divides the members.
This is barely enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
The two sides are now in a period of mutual trial and testing for signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and voter patience for a renewed partisan war.
That’s why Tuesday’s meeting and subsequent comments from participants unveiled a minimum of requirements or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and Republicans are too big and too deep to suggest a rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it's taxes, expenses, health care or fees, both sides remain miles apart.
Yet the November election had moderated Washington, at least in the short term.
“There is no doubt that things have changed in tone,” said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official, now alongside the Center for Ethical and Public Policy.
“This is inevitable after the election.
Elections arouse partisan passions and then fade away.
That's good."
On certain issues, notably those on the agenda of the "lame duck" session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts will expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of that.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all of them, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise is possible on the extension of unemployment benefits, if only because Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favour of tax cuts for the rich, while refusing unemployment benefits to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, more optimism is hovering over a possible agreement on the issues raised during the session on the "lame duck", with the ratification of the "New START" pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that fruitful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the "blade duck" session will not necessarily lead to better understanding between the two parties when the 112th Congress meets in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely, if not inevitable.
“Once the things that need to be done are done, the psychology in the short term will come back to one of the confrontations,” he said.
Wehner also expressed his widely shared skepticism that civility would lead to true cooperation.
“I consider most of what’s going on between today and 2012 as a pre-show or shadow-boxing compared to the main event of 2012,” he said.
The reasons are closely related to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters present at the tea that contributed to its creation.
However, Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know they must try to live up to their promises to reduce public spending and repeal the new health care law.
These partisan positions are already clear in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the deficit commission which include reforming the tax code and raising certain taxes, pushing back the retirement age and reducing spending.
Co-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles chose one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and, according to them, imposed the deficit issue on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes on the 18-member committee to issue their plan as an official recommendation, and they have struggled to reach that number.
The greatest resistance remains among the group's elected representatives, suggesting that there are, at least today, few grounds or willingness to compromise on tax issues.
Galston foresees two phases in the fighting between the White House and Congressional Republicans.
The first will come in the form of partisan clashes next year, as Republicans challenge Obama on budget, taxes and health care; followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would be the cause of the change?
Public opinion.
It is widely proven that, despite the partisan spirit of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see both parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a stalemate, as in 1995, then both parties will carefully observe the reaction of the public.
The one who will be judged at a loss will have to change course and find compromises.
But that would still be an optimistic view.
The partisan spirit and polarization is greater today than it was in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and Congressional Republicans than there was then between President Bill Clinton and Republicans.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a more substantial election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility exposed this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
