On the other hand, Vice President Elena Salgado, with the support of former President Felipe González, joins Chancellor Angela Merkel’s criticism of her responsibility to detach the current crisis.
How should these movements be interpreted?
It should be mentioned that Merkel’s position is not a mistake in her communicative policy.
On the contrary, it is another constraint on the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And here Germany has a radically new vision of what its future must be, which clashes with that of maintaining the old traditions of most of its partners.
In the face of European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate on the three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first, a strong euro, integrated by itself, Austria and Holland, among other countries, and the south would abandon the monetary zone.
The second, the recovery of the Mark, even if now it seems like science fiction, with a very favorable current of opinion, nearly 50% of the population.
The third, a new conception of the euro, in line with the German proposals for greater macroeconomic control, fiscal rigour, fines to countries that violate them, possible suspensions of payments from one of them and extension to the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and has been defined for a long time, so now there is no room for excuses.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission were stimulating deficits, the German government invented a constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016 onwards.
This was the first sign of divergence between what Germany thought should be done (fiscal rigour and fiscal stability plans) and what its European partners, including France, were doing.
The Central European country’s second blow was when Merkel hardly extended the decision to save Greece.
Since then it has been the subject of fierce criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public opinion and the published one were against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, towards the end of October, Merkel again expressed a clear position, calling for reform of the EU treaties to make it possible to rescue a country and at the same time oblige private lenders to bear a part of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, as it has precipitated the Irish crisis and the rest.
But his proposal, although somewhat softened, has been approved, and in the months ahead we should be witnessing the EU reform process that makes these measures possible from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not think will cross.
And it tells us all that, even if we now have to take measures with which we may not be too much in agreement, from that date onwards the old functioning of the euro would have ended.
2013 will mean the birth of a new monetary zone, in which countries that break the rules will be severely punished, they may be forced to declare themselves in default and, in that case, the private sector will also bear a share of the costs.
Germany tells us that we need to follow a strong growth path with high savings and investment rates, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
An alternative based on debt and construction, with huge holes in the balance of payments, like the one that presided over Spanish growth in the boom years, will simply not be tolerated.
The bet is clear.
And it would be wrong not to hear it.
It is not just a question of bringing the government deficit back to 3% in 2013.
What we're being asked for is much harder.
And what he absolutely must not do in these circumstances is deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will bring greater tranquility to us.
And let us know how to seize the opportunity that we have been given, until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero has also heard it in this form and his dual statement (the reforms promised after last Saturday's meeting with big business and yesterday's announcement of new measures) suggests that, despite Merkel's criticism, the path has been opened to the thesis that it is necessary to put order at home.
But the red line that Germany has drawn is there, and they don’t seem to move it.
And among the possibilities envisaged, we cannot exclude the possibility of abandoning a monetary zone too drunk of countries that are not serious.
And in that case, Germany will always be able to tell us that it had warned us about it.
Sport and Law Fraud
The tricks similar to those of Alonso and Ramos against Ajax demonstrate the ingenuity but not the willingness to escape a sanction.
The expulsion in principle by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) during the November 23 match against Ajax in the Champions League has caused a lot of ink to flow on the unsportsmanlike character of such behavior and whether both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is known, just minutes before finishing the match (which their team already clearly won), both players deliberately lost time when they made mistakes to determine the referee to show them the second yellow card.
Thus, and given that Real Madrid will eventually be the leader of its group, both players will comply with the regulatory sanction during the next match of the playoff match against Auxerre and will be able to pass without cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee sanctioned the team's coach, José Mourinho, with two matches and different amounts of money to the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, if not rather common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, the unwritten rules, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate that emerged in the related case is due to the fact that this had as protagonist a team of the entity of Real Madrid (who in his anthem displays nobility and honor and who in past occasions has condemned to a fine his players for similar acts) and to the orchestrated dramatization, it seems, by the more provocative and historical episode, by Mourinho, who adds to his de
In any case, the debate asks whether this type of behaviour is not expressly prohibited by the regulation, which contradicts the principles of sport, that is to say, whether these actions are committed as a fraud of law, because, indeed, they are actions respectful of the sport regulation, but seem to elude its meaning.
The question is to examine the type of harm they cause to the sporting mind.
One of the assets that includes the sporting spirit is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that with these actions has not been endangered, that is to say, there has not been a violent game.
Another of these assets referred to with correct play is to prevent the team of the offending players from unfairly taking advantage of the opposing team, which is not the case either.
However, the paradoxical fact of the action of Real Madrid players is that it does not accommodate what is normally characterized as cheating or fraud of the law, because its violation of the rules was not carried out secretly to try to avoid the sanction, but their action has precisely tried to be as obvious as possible to receive the penalty from the referee.
They waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another issue is the type of benefit that offenders get from the intentional misconducts examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that you do not put the opponent at a disadvantage and you do not get an advantage in the same match either, because obviously the result of the action assumes the fact of leaving their own team with fewer players.
And that’s not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club could not count on these players.
Obviously the advantage is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, because the team could be eliminated suddenly and apart from that, with this action the players complete a penalty match and move on to the second round of cards, in which the suspension due to the accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first round.
So, climbing the ladder, it is not so clear that this is an advantage.
Ultimately, these actions are not contrary to the sporting spirit, of which strategic decisions that promote profit to the maximum of what the rules allow are still part.
In our case, the players did not act to avoid the application of the sanction (this would indeed be a clear case of fraud of the law), otherwise they chose instead the time in which they submitted to it.
They made a strategic decision without thwarting the penalty or running away from it.
Even though the boundary between genius and law fraud is blurred, on this occasion I think we had a clear case of genius.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises because of two factors: because there have been two self-expulsions and because of the way of transmitting the director to provoke them.
The harm caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not as ethical as it is aesthetic.
