Pakistan's nuclear program raises great concern in the United States
Islamabad produces atomic weapons at "a faster rate than any other country".
WikiLeaks leaks confirm connection between Taliban and Pakistan
The contents of the correspondence between the U.S. Embassy in Pakistan and the U.S. State Department leaked by the Wikileaks portal confirm the enormous concerns that the Pakistani nuclear program is causing in Washington.
Aside from the enlightening and tasty details that offer about the content of the conversations and thoughts of North American diplomatic representatives accredited to Islamabad, the documents reveal the fact that cooperation between the two countries in the field of atomic security, instead of increasing, is "declining" and that the unstable Asian country produces nuclear weapons "at a faster rate than any other country in the world".
The peculiarity of Pakistan's nuclear program - the fact that the weapons are not assembled, but are stored by components to make it difficult to destroy them in the event of an attack - is one of the main reasons for concern in Washington.
The ambassador to Pakistan, Anne W. Patterson, lists in a report before the visit of the former National Security Adviser, James Jones: "The proximity of certain nuclear facilities to the territory under Taliban attack, the dispersion of nuclear materials whose noise is short and the vulnerability of the transport of atomic materials."
The large number of people involved in nuclear arsenals and missile programs is considered, not only by the United States, but also by Russia, as proliferating and a reason to maintain guard.
“Pakistan has been hiring staff with strict religious beliefs to protect nuclear facilities; given the falling educational and cultural levels, extremist organizations have more opportunities to recruit people who work in nuclear or missile programs,” Russian Foreign Ministry expert Yuri Korolev said during a meeting with his US counterparts.
The new documentation filtered by the portal of Julian Assange is the increasingly reduced cooperation between the United States and Pakistan in the field of nuclear proliferation and the high Pakistani degree of production of nuclear weapons.
An embassy dispatch in May, which calls communication with Pakistan "frustrating", argues that "transparency is often non-existent; aid offers remain unanswered or are being eliminated".
In another message, Peter Lavoy, a national intelligence official for South Asia, noted that “despite the economic catastrophe, Pakistan is producing nuclear weapons at a faster rate than any other country in the world.”
Ambassador Patterson also asked Washington, during a visit by the head of the army, General Ashfaq Kayani, to make it "very clear" to the official that "the Pakistan Army must end tacit support for terrorist groups".
