China is continuing its bid to cut its greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent before 2020, said Su Wei, China’s representative at COP16.
In his first public appearance at the 16th Conference of the Parties to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (COP16), Su Wei assured that his country has made enormous efforts to reduce the trace of coal and reconvert its industry.
In fact, he explained, over the past four years his country has invested $245 million in efforts to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
Nonetheless, he made it clear that China will not change its objectives, but will continue to work together with the international community in this area.
He noted that China's climate change strategy is divided into four areas: dialogue; capacity building; institution building; and pilot programme support.
Progress has been made in all of these areas, including the approval last year of a new Energy Act that recognizes the goals being addressed in reducing greenhouse gases, he said.
On the other hand, he stressed that in China, federal authorities have worked in a coordinated manner with government and local governments to achieve energy saving, energy efficiency and emission reduction goals.
In addition, he said, there are various multi-year plans underway or completed, both funded by the Chinese government and the governments of other countries.
For example, he mentioned the Energy Efficient Use Program, which has been implemented for the past five years and has received investments from the United Nations (UN), the government and private initiative.
There is also a provincial climate change project, another for the change of incandescent lamps by economy lamps and another for mitigation and adaptation, he detailed.
At the same table, Martin Krol, the country’s government’s scientific advisor on climate change, said China’s efforts have been greater than people think.
For example, he explained, per capita greenhouse gas emissions in China are three tons per person, while in the United States it is 100 tons; China is responsible for 9% of the historical contribution to contamination.
