A global plan to renovate lighting
The UN proposed yesterday in Cancún a plan to renovate domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to achieve a greenhouse gas (GHG) reduction that is almost one-third of the additional reduction needed to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is in the wake of the major concrete projects that the United Nations hopes to have adopted in Cancún to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments by industrialized countries.
According to the plan tabled yesterday, if incandescent bulbs that still monopolize 50 to 70% of the market were replaced by fluorescent compact bulbs or, better, light-emitting diode (LED) bulbs, the bulk of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GHG emitted on the planet to illuminate humans would be replaced.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is the equivalent of 70% of the global car fleet’s emissions.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitting countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that are expected to increase global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will be necessary to subtract from this balance another 5 Gt to stabilize by 2020 the rise of the climate to 2 degrees centigrade in order to avoid that it becomes out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat and the rest, or 5%, produces light.
With compact fluorescent light bulbs, energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, this energy requirement is reduced by two times more.
Compact fluorescent bulbs last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched by manufacturer Philips this week - this company participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, giving an idea of the possible economy with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These brand new bulbs can also work with rheostats in addition to emitting very little heat.
They do not contain any mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations about compact fluorescent light bulbs because they contain mercury and need to be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless manufacturers put in place instructions.
But, the report says, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the compact fluorescent bulb, but rather coal-fired power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce electricity wasted in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tonnes of mercury per year.
The report details the gains that each country would make through this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save $1 billion a year in electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants costing $2.5 billion to build.
