The unemployment rate in France within the meaning of the International Labour Office (ILO) remained stable at 9.3% in the metropolis (9.7% including the overseas departments), show the seasonally adjusted data (CVS) provisional published Thursday by the INSEE.
The number of unemployed stands at 2.631 million in the metropolis.
The data for the second quarter were confirmed to 9.3% of the working population in the metropolitan area and 9.7% with the DOM.
Over a year, the unemployment rate rose by 0.1 points.
More broadly, 3.4 million people in metropolitan France did not work in the third quarter but wanted to work, whether or not they were available within two weeks to work and whether or not they were looking for a job.
The situation of young people in the labour market has deteriorated further, with the unemployment rate rising again to 24.2% in the metropolitan area (+0.9 points over three months, +0.5 points over one year) and 25% including the DOM.
In the third quarter, 637,000 youth aged 15 to 24 were unemployed within the meaning of the ILO.
The elderly experienced a slight increase in unemployment, to 6.4% in the metropolis (+0.2 points over three months as well as one year), or 482,000 people aged 50 years or more, and 6.6% with the DOM.
Only 25-49-year-olds benefited from stable unemployment in the third quarter, at 8.3% in metropolitan France (-0.1 points over three months, +0.1 points over a year) and 8.8% in all of France.
INSEE has not published monthly unemployment rates since 2006, after a controversy over its method of calculation.
Eurostat, the European Union's statistical agency, continues to do so and announced on Tuesday a rate of 9.8% for France (DOM included) in October after 9.9% in September.
