Avengers and spies on diligence
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it is an apparent scandal, a scandal that appears as a scandal only in the face of the hypocrisy that governs the relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it heralds profound changes at the international level, and foreshadows a future dominated by regression.
But let's proceed in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file constituted by a secret service (of any nation) is composed exclusively of press cuts.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits only report what could have been read in any newspaper for months (except those Berlusconi owns), and Gaddafi's sinisterly caricatured profile has long been for sketch-matter cabaret artists.
The rule that secret files should be composed only of new ones already known is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rose-Croix) exactly what was already written in the previous works.
And this is not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do unpublished research (nor does he know where to look for news about the inexisting), but because those who dedicate themselves to occultism believe only in what they already know, and which reconfirms what they had already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
Same goes for the secret files.
The whistleblower is lazy, and lazy (or of limited mind) the head of the secret services (otherwise he could be, what do I know, editor at Liberation), who holds as true only what he recognizes.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi that the US embassy in Rome sent to the State Department was the same as Newsweek published the week before.
So why did the revelations on these files make so much noise?
On the one hand, they say what any educated person already knows, namely that embassies, at least since the end of the Second World War, and since heads of state can telephone or take a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small representation exercises, have turned into espionage centers.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is only by hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore it.
However, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to put American diplomacy in a bad light.
Second, the idea that any hacker could capture the most secrets of the world’s most powerful country is a major blow to the State Department’s prestige.
Therefore, the scandal does not put the victims as much into crisis as the “bureaus”.
But let us come to the deeper nature of what happened.
In the time of Orwell, one could conceive of all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy had proved completely since, being able to control every movement through the phone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway taken, and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the eye of power.
But when it is demonstrated, as it is now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker – elected as the citizen’s avenger – can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that any knowledge of the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed an empty secret, because it is in the public domain; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks has done, that the secrets of Hillary Clinton were empty secrets means to her.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but has done too much to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound inflicted on a very powerful power?
It is clear that in the future, states will no longer be able to post any confidential information - it would be like publishing it on a poster glued to the corner.
But it is just as obvious that with current technologies, it is futile to hope to maintain confidential reports over the phone.
There is nothing easier than to find out if and when a head of state travelled by plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and confidential relations be maintained in the future?
I know well that, for the moment, my prediction is science fiction and is therefore novelistic, but I am obliged to imagine government agents moving discreetly in diligences to uncontrollable routes, carrying only messages learned by heart or, at most, hiding the rare information written in the heel of a heel.
The information will be kept as a single copy in locked drawers: basically, the Watergate espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is now advancing in crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet has restored a wired (telephone) telegraph.
Videotapes (analog) had allowed film researchers to explore a film step by step, going back and forth and discovering all the secrets of editing, while now CDs (digital) only allow jumping from chapter to chapter, that is, in macro-portions.
With high-speed trains, you get from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, and the commutes that it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
It is therefore not extraordinary that the politics and communications techniques come back to horse-drawn cars.
One last observation.
In the past, the press tried to understand what was going on in the secret embassies.
Now it is the embassies that ask the press for confidential information.
Climate: How France Bribes Its Promises of Financing
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine the fulfilment of the promises of fast-start or early-start financing made by developed countries.
And the big French masterminds are revealed.
In the Copenhagen agreement, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union pledged <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion over three years and France <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1.26 billion (or <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>420 million per year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU launched the big game to persuade its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start financing: report detailing the action of its member states, press conference, big side event, distribution of brochures...
Transparency is appreciated and valued: developing countries and civil society would like to see all developed countries do the same with the same level of precision.
The EU announced that it had released <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to meet its commitment of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look at it in detail, things are more complicated.
This money must, according to the Copenhagen Agreement, be "new and additional" in order to ensure that an additional effort is made without being to the detriment of Official Development Assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that best suits them.
For example, the European Commission has taken 2009 as a benchmark: international funding is maintained, and it adds <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>150 million over three years for fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks in terms of year or level of official development assistance.
In contrast, France considers that funding for "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to spending in previous years or at the overall level of Official Development Assistance.
Concretely, the total amount of support from France to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to respect its commitment in terms of "new and additional" financing...
Another crucial element is the distribution between grants and loans.
Again, there is no rule and everyone chooses their calculation method.
Some, like France, consider that 1 <0xE2><0x82><0xAC> lent is equivalent to 1 <0xE2><0x82><0xAC> given.
Obviously, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to the mitigation of emissions that rely on more efficient technologies), it is fallacious to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to one euro that is given ... At most, it should be counted under its commitments only the cost of the loan for the lending country.
But France has nothing to do with such reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euros) - see the EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (in others) meet their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union puts in <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1 to meet its commitment, France puts in only 10 cents and considers the effort to be comparable.
Nice pass trick!
In summary, in its fast start financing, France operates a double scam: on the one hand on the evolution of the action over time and on the other on the reality of the financial effort.
By spending only <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>36.1 million, it manages to make it seem that it is spending <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>420 million "new and additional" in line with its promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that Bercy made the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other member states continue to give if it is enough to lend?) and in the negotiations since the developing countries are not completely fooled...
The chapter on early financing is only a small, relatively short-term issue compared to all the climate discussions.
But it could be one more grain of sand in the immense machine that is the UNFCCC.
Hopefully this will not be the case.
In any case, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its method of accounting for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and fairness with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could advance the discussions on the issues of long-term financing (another crucial chapter currently discussed): we will not escape the question of "additionality" or the method of accounting for loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
So hope rests on the new Minister of the Environment, Mrs. Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement on France's fast start and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans would increase the level of international confidence needed to move forward in the discussions.
Alert to pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemicals in one day, according to a study published Wednesday by the association Generations Futures (ex-Movement for rights and respect for future generations).
The association, which warns that its results "do not have significant statistical value in the light of the small number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem addressed", bought between July and September the foods usually consumed in four meals and a snack in a day by a child of about ten years, in the supermarkets of Oise and Paris.
These standard meals, including official recommendations - five fresh fruits and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day - as well as treats, were reviewed by laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance of the plate is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, 42 of which are classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five substances classified as certain carcinogens, as well as 37 substances that can act as endocrine disruptors (EP), according to studies by several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Centre.
"Although, in almost all cases, the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded, our investigation clearly shows that the reality of consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic contaminants and/or PE is of concern," the association notes.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three proven to be carcinogenic, as well as nearly twenty residues likely to disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, planned as a snack by the study, has traces of six chemicals including a fungicide yet banned in France.
The same goes for Kenyan green beans, included in lunch, on which the study detected traces of a potent insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, chopped steak, canned tuna, and even breadstick and chewing gum were filled with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, analyses revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
